00:32.333 --> 00:35.624
Anyway, to cut a long story short,

00:35.625 --> 00:37.943
I decided to kill myself.

00:39.625 --> 00:41.999
That's the trouble with
suicides, I've learnt.

00:42.000 --> 00:44.082
You can't cut the long story short,

00:44.083 --> 00:48.060
because it's the long story
that people are interested in.

00:48.292 --> 00:49.749
Especially if you're me,

00:49.750 --> 00:52.499
which, regrettably, I was

00:52.500 --> 00:54.874
and still am to this day.

00:54.875 --> 00:59.957
So, forgive me if you already
knew this, but I'm Martin Sharp,

00:59.958 --> 01:01.624
the man who had everything.

01:01.625 --> 01:06.124
One wife, two children, three dogs,
at least four People's Choice awards,

01:06.125 --> 01:10.860
and five mornings a week on the most
successful breakfast show in Britain.

01:11.333 --> 01:14.647
Huh, they were even
offering me Mondays off.

01:15.583 --> 01:17.273
So far, so good.

01:17.292 --> 01:21.980
I had reached middle age
unscathed, with money in the bank.

01:22.875 --> 01:28.249
Until I met Susie Jenkins at a
launch for a new men's moisturiser.

01:28.250 --> 01:30.957
- Happy New Year, mate.
- All I can say in my defence, Your Honour,

01:30.958 --> 01:33.644
is that she looked 25 to me.

01:33.833 --> 01:35.559
But she wasn't.

01:36.583 --> 01:38.624
Cue, in chronological order,

01:38.625 --> 01:42.291
tabloid frenzy, a short
prison sentence, divorce,

01:42.292 --> 01:45.605
disgrace, demolition.

01:45.833 --> 01:48.318
Doors closing.

01:48.458 --> 01:51.707
New Year's Eve is supposed
to be a pause for breath,

01:51.708 --> 01:53.707
a punctuation mark.

01:53.708 --> 01:56.499
Well, I had come to a full stop.

01:56.500 --> 01:57.707
Really.

01:57.708 --> 02:01.520
Why wouldn't I want to throw myself
off the top of a tall building?

03:22.875 --> 03:25.311
Oh! Oh!

03:43.958 --> 03:45.815
Excuse me.

03:46.042 --> 03:47.980
Excuse me.

03:50.042 --> 03:51.416
Hi.

03:51.417 --> 03:55.394
Um, I'm not entirely sure
how to phrase this, but...

03:56.500 --> 03:58.356
Are you going to be long?

03:58.708 --> 04:02.354
- What?
- I wasn't sure whether to wait my turn, or...

04:02.708 --> 04:06.401
I hadn't considered the wire. I'd
really like to borrow your ladder.

04:06.833 --> 04:09.541
Maybe I should just
wait. I'll wait.

04:09.542 --> 04:10.874
Are you just going to
stand there and watch?

04:10.875 --> 04:15.149
No. No, of course. You'll be wanting
to do it on your own, I'd imagine.

04:15.208 --> 04:17.124
You imagine right.

04:17.125 --> 04:19.666
I'll go there.

04:19.666 --> 04:21.226
All right.

04:24.542 --> 04:27.026
I'll give you a
shout on the way down.

04:27.667 --> 04:29.226
Right.

04:38.958 --> 04:40.684
Oh, jeez!

04:52.417 --> 04:53.976
I can't.

04:54.500 --> 04:56.356
Maybe you should go first.

04:56.833 --> 04:59.069
I would want to be on my own.

04:59.250 --> 05:01.734
- Completely.
- Understood.

05:02.458 --> 05:05.902
Twenty minutes, then
I want my spot back.

05:08.375 --> 05:10.182
- Right.
- OK.

05:15.958 --> 05:17.945
- Ooh!
- Oh!

05:32.250 --> 05:33.976
Maureen.

05:35.167 --> 05:36.774
Martin.

05:38.375 --> 05:40.101
Are you from...

05:40.333 --> 05:44.499
- Oh, I... I recognise your face.
- Oh, do you?

05:44.500 --> 05:46.749
Were you married to
someone in a pop group?

05:46.750 --> 05:48.309
No.

05:48.958 --> 05:52.541
- Were you on TV?
- Maureen, perhaps this is not

05:52.542 --> 05:54.610
the best time to talk about this.

06:03.333 --> 06:05.332
- Out of my way, fuckers!
- No, stop, stop!

06:05.333 --> 06:06.541
No! No!

06:06.542 --> 06:09.357
- Maureen, a bit of help?
- Who the fuck are you?

06:09.417 --> 06:11.666
